<DOC><DOCNO> AP880603-0272 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 0151EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   06-03 0501</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0519</SECOND><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Consumers continued to spend at a slow pace in May, the nation'slargest general retailers reported, and Wall Street analysts saidthe slump could continue through much of the summer.   High installment debt, an aversion to higher prices and boredomwith current fashions _ the same factors that have kept consumerscautious for months _ contributed to the lackluster May performanceand were exacerbated by the unusually cool spring, analysts saidThursday.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Financier Carl C. Icahn sought to turn up theheat in his fight with Texaco Inc., calling together securitiesanalysts to try to convince them he has the means _ and the will _to follow through on his takeover bid.   Icahn offered last week to buy the 86.2 percent of the company'sstock he does not already own for $60 a share, or $12.4 billion.The bid put a total value on Texaco's 207 million shares of $14.6billion.   Texaco's directors rejected the offer Friday, prompting Icahn,the company's largest shareholder, to go through with his threat towage a proxy fight for five seats on the oil giant's board.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Burlington Northern Inc., owner of the nation'slargest railroad, announced a major restructuring that includesseparating non-transportation operations into a subsidiary thateventually will be spun off as a separate company.   On Thursday, the Seattle-based company said it was seeking tosell a 13 percent stake in its recently formed Burlington ResourcesInc. to the public and raise around $500 million for possiblefuture expansion. The unit contains Burlington Northern's energy,natural resource and real estate operations.</TEXT><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   FMC Corp. moved toward increased weapons sales inthe Middle East by signing a $1 billion pact to jointly producearmored vehicles for Turkey and announcing a $400 million sale toSaudi Arabia.   The Saudi order, approved by Congress last month and announcedThursday, represents Chicago-based FMC's first foreign sales of itsBradley Fighting Vehicle and could open the door for similar salesto other friendly countries in the region, a spokeswoman said.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The standard of living of workers in othermajor countries has risen four times as fast as the U.S. standardof living in the past 15 years, according to a new study onAmerican competitiveness.   The report, prepared by the Council on Competitiveness andreleased Thursday, concluded that the United States had lost groundnot only in terms of living standards, but also in the relatedareas of international trade, productivity and investment.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Billionaire computer pioneer H. Ross Perotlaunched a new business with the U.S. Postal Service as his firstclient _ a contract to help find ways to cut costs and improveservice.   The $500,000 deal, announced Thursday, calls for Perot's newcompany, Perot Systems Corp., to study five specific areas ofpostal performance and recommend methods of saving money withbetter efficiency.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>